gen_desc: Located in northern Baltimore County, the Hereford Area’s 3,620 acres feature a scenic wilderness setting preserved under state Wildlands status for nature appreciation and outdoor adventures. Anglers can enjoy a nationally renowned special trout management area located downstream from Prettyboy Reservoir, and hikers and horseback riders can explore more than 20 miles of wooded trails. The Big Gunpowder Falls also attracts canoeing, kayaking and tubing enthusiasts throughout the year
ecology: Trails

id: \nHikers and horseback riders are welcome on the Hereford Area’s 20-miles of trails. This is a state designated Wildlands Area: bicycles are strictly prohibited.
\nPlease stay on designated trails. The trails in this area are steep and rocky and potentially slippery.

gen_desc: Susquehanna State Park

id: \nLocated along the Susquehanna River valley with its heavy forest cover and rocky terrain, Susquehanna State Park offers a wide variety of outdoor recreational opportunities. The park is home to some of the most popular mountain biking trails in Maryland and the river itself beckons fishermen and boaters alike. Susquehanna State Park also contains a family friendly campground with traditional campsites and cabins. History buffs will be drawn to the restored Rock Run Historic Area with its working gristmill, the Carter-Archer Mansion, Jersey Toll House and the remains of the Susquehanna & Tidewater Canal.
\nThe river offers excellent fishing opportunities, including pike, perch, and bass for shoreline anglers or boating anglers who launch from the Lapidum Boat Ramp.
location_id: Trails

id: \nSusquehanna State Park contains over 15 miles of marked and maintained trails; ideal for hikers, mountain bikers, equestrians and nature lovers. The terrain varies throughout the river valley. The different trails have ratings ranging from easy to difficult. The Lower Susquehanna Heritage Greenways Trail runs between the Conowingo Dam and Stafford Road at Deer Creek and is an excellent flat trail for family hike and bike outings. It is also handicapped accessible.

\nSusquehanna Ridge Trail - Blazed in red, the trail goes from the Picnic Area to Lapidum following the western ridge of the Susquehanna River. The Ridge Trail is approximately three miles in distance with moderate to difficult climbs. The trail provides magnificent views of the Susquehanna River Valley.

\nLand of Promise - Blazed in white, the trail starts at the Ridge Trail a short distance from the Lapidum Trail Head. The Land of Promise is of moderate difficulty and is 1.6 miles in distance. The trail ends at the Rock Run Historic Area by the mansion driveway.

\nFarm Road Trail - Blazed in dark blue, the trail starts in the Deer Creek Picnic Area following a farm road through fields and forests. The Farm Trail is moderate in difficulty and is two miles in distance. The trail crosses both Wilkinson and Rock Run Roads and ends at the Rock Run Y Trail.

\nRock Run Y Trail - Blazed in yellow, the trail begins at Quaker Bottom Road. The trail forks in the pine plantation. The right fork will intersect with the Land of Promise Trail. The left fork intersects with the Farm Road Trail and continues on and intersects the Land of Promise Trail. Moderate difficulty with a distance of .9 miles.

\nIvy Branch Trail - Blazed in orange, this trail begins at the intersection of Rock Run and Wilkinson Roads. The trail crosses the Farm Road Trail, Wilkinson Road and through farm fields. An easy to moderate trail with a distance of two miles.

\nDeer Creek Trail - Blazed in green, the trail begins and ends at the Picnic Area. The Deer Creek Trail has magnificent views and giant trees. A moderate to difficult trail with a distance of 2.1 miles.

\nLower Susquehanna Heritage Greenways Trail - Marked with Greenways emblems at half mile intervals, a 2.2 mile improved section runs between Conowingo Dam and Stafford Road at Deer Creek. This trail is accessible from the Deer Creek Picnic Area or Conowingo Dam parking area. A one mile unimproved section continues along the Susquehanna, bringing you to the trestle bridge at the mouth of Deer Creek. The Greenways trail continues on a 3 mile unimproved section by following the Susquehanna Ridge Trail from the trestle or picnic area to Lapidum.
\nSpur Trails - The Spur Trails connect trails to expand your travels through Susquehanna State Park.

gen_desc: Eden Mill Nature Center

location_id: Trail Information -

id: \nEden Mill has miles of trails leading to a beautiful overlook of the creek and EMNC! Each is maintained by volunteers for easy hiking.
\nTrail Information Trail Ratings: ·  Easy ·  Moderate ·  Most Difficult
\n·  Pollipot Trail: Starts at Mill and follows wetlands along Big Branch Creek to main trailhead. Parts are elevated on boardwalk. Length: approx. 0.3 miles
\n·  Beaver Run Trail: Follows Deer Creek with plenty to see - beavers, birds, turtles, plants. Length: approx. 0.29 miles
\n·  Bluebird Trail: Succession Area, foxes, rabbits, deer, blue birds, easy hiking. Length: approx. 0.17 miles
\n·  Mingo Trail: Follows the upper meadow, best birding trail in the park. Length: approx. 0.19 miles

\n·  Cedar Run Trail: Cedar Run Trail follows the edge of the forest along one side, and a meadow along the other side. This trail joins up with Laurel Ridge Trail at Switchbacks. Length: approx. 0.19 miles
\n·  High Meadow Trail: Starts at main trailhead. Follows the edge of the High Meadow and forest. Steep climb at beginning of trail. Length: approx. 0.3 miles
\n·  Laurel Ridge Trail: A forest Trail overlooking Deer Creek. At the end is 400 feet of switchbacks that join up with Beaver Run Trail. Length: approx. 0.18 miles
\n·  Birds Nest Trail: Wooded, good birding. Length: approx. 0.06 miles
\n·  Fox Run Trail: New growth, plenty of deer signs, rabbits, and birds. Length: approx. 0.14 miles

gen_desc: The Torrey C. Brown Rail Trail extends from Ashland, Maryland north to the Maryland-Pennsylvania line, and passes through historic communities including Ashland, Phoenix, Monkton, White Hall, Bentley Springs and Freeland. Hikers, joggers, bicyclists, horseback riders and pets on leashes are welcome. The TCB Rail Trail users are welcome to continue their journey north into Pennsylvania by traveling on the York County Heritage Trail.

id: \nNorthern Central Railroad Trail is a 19.4 mile moderately trafficked point-to-point trail located near White Hall, Maryland that features a river and is good for all skill levels. The trail offers a number of activity options and is accessible year-round.
gen_desc: http://dnr2.maryland.gov/publiclands/Pages/central/tcb.aspx
502 W Wheel Rd.

id: \nHarford Glen is made available to the public as a courtesy for nature recreation purposes during limited times throughout the year.  Passive activities, such as hiking, bird watching, family outings, picnicking, and nature observation are encouraged at the center.
location_id: Riparian

id: \n◦Weekends only beginning the first weekend in April through the last weekend in October, 7:00 AM to 7:00 PM on Saturdays and Sundays.

\n◦Over the summer when school is not in session, seven days per week, 7:00 AM to 7:00 PM, beginning in June after the last day of school for HCPS students and ending in August before school begins for HCPS students.
\n◦November 1 to March 30: Closed to public; open for school business only.
\nA general rule to remember is if Harford County Public Schools are in session, then Harford Glen is closed to the public.

location_id: http://www.hcps.org/harfordglen/home%20page/index.html

gen_desc: The site of the famous Battle of Wisconsin Heights during Black Hawk Wars, hence the name.
ecology: Typical bluff rising over Wisconsin River Valley, mostly forested.
species: Lots of downed wood. Sports large quantities of wood shelves, Stereum and other wood-dwellers.
notes: Several parking areas and interconnecting trails. Wachter road leading up to the top, where there is winter shelter, horse pavilion, portable bathrooms and summer shelter. The gate on the road is closed though, except for special events, so one needs to ascend half mile of a steep incline.

gen_desc: Full name is Browntown-Caddiz Springs State Recreation Area. Was created in 1980 by combining Browntown Wildlife area and Caddiz Springs State Park.
ecology: Two lakes are the centerpiece of the park. Both have been created by damming the creek, since this area of Wisconsin (called "driftless") doesn't have natural lakes.
species: The park itself is angled more toward fishing and recreation on the lakes, and system of trails doesn't go through quality woods. However, part of the site is Browntown Oak Forest State Natural Area, that has richer flora and some mushrooms.
notes: Requires Wisconsin State Park sticker.

gen_desc: County Park on the East Shore of Lake Winnebago, near Stockbridge, WI.
ecology: The Niagara Escarpment is prominent in the park.
species: Dolomite - associated lichen species can be found.
notes: Indian Mounds are present on the property.

gen_desc: County Park on the East Shore of Lake Winnebago, near Stockbridge, WI.
ecology: The Niagara Escarpment is prominent in the park.
species: Dolomite - associated lichen species can be found.
notes: Indian Mounds are present on the property.

gen_desc: Camp Douglas is a village along the Interstate 90-94 between Madison and Lacrosse, WI.
ecology: The place of interest in Camp Douglas is so called "Back 40" land parcel, acquired for public use. It has trails weaving around sandstone formations and up and down hills in the forest.
species: Species of lichen associated with shaded sandstone bluffs.
notes: Access is free.

gen_desc: Rock County Park near Janesville, Wisconsin.
ecology: Park is dominated by Spring Brook Creek, cutting deep channel in the rock and exposing layered dolomite formations.
species: Lichens dwelling on dolomite can be found here. Plants include more northern species that found shelter under the moist cool cliff.
notes: The park includes Carver-Roehl Woods State Natural Area

gen_desc: Bluffs facing Mississippi River.
ecology: Open bluff and goat prairies, wooded back side of the bluffs.
species: Very rare in Wisconsin Chinquapin Oak savanna and its associated ground layer is present on the site. Goat prairies have interesting species of lichen on weathered dolomite boulders and outcrops.
notes: Free to visit. Need to climb the steep bluffs.

gen_desc: A recently acquired Columbus and Franklin County Metro Parks property. Second-growth hardwood forest in very good condition. Quercus alba very abundant and forming almost pure stands in some spots. Permit required for collecting.
Part of Black River State Forest, located along Interstate 90 corridor.
ecology: A ridge running east-west, made of 400 million old Cambrian Sandstone; has two distinctive microclimates on the north and south slopes of the ridge.
species: Species of lichen typical of sandstones; sun-loving on the exposed parts of the butte, and moisture-dependent in the deep shade at the bottom of the cliff.
notes: WI State Parks parking permit may be required (not sure).

gen_desc: Located on the east side of the Door Peninsula, just north of Whitefish Dunes State Park.
ecology: Known for underwater caves (sometimes showing above the surf) formed by the lake and wind action in the dolomite backbone of the Door Peninsula (Niagara Escarpment). Windswept shoreline.
species: Plenty of rare lichens. In particular, Anaptychia setifera is thick on the leeward side of trees lining shoreline.
notes: It seems there is no parking fee

gen_desc: Small town northeast of Madison, WI
species: Incidental find of the mushroom in a city lawn. Appears to be Mycenastrum corium.

gen_desc: Located in the 1000-acre depression in Marquette County, WI.
ecology: Quacking sedge medow
species: Lichen and mushrooms in the thin forest surrounding the marsh.
notes: Free access.

gen_desc: Within Avon Bottoms State Wildlife Area, Rock County, WI
ecology: Floodplain forest along Sugar River, and wet prairie on higher ground.
species: Sycamores can be found in the woods, at their northernmost range limit here.
notes: Free access.

gen_desc: Rapids in Wisconsin River near Stevens Point, WI.
ecology: Large exposed expanses of gneisses and other intrusive volcanic rocks on the shores and in the stream of Wisconsin River.
species: Number of acid-loving lichen species on flat rock exposures.
notes: Free public access from River Road.

gen_desc: This area was set aside a while ago, and is being turned into the public area, but the status of the future park is not clear yet. On some maps it appears as a State Park, but there is no signs of the State Park on the ground yet. Some land is federal, and some is owned by the state. There are indicators that the area will be an Ice Age Reserve. Presently, the Ice Age Trail is being put through the area.
ecology: The significance of this parcel of land is it's situated right on the border between glaciated and "driftless" (unglaciated) areas of Wisconsin. This is precisely where the glacier stopped tens of thousands of 2years ago, before retreating northward.
species: Can contain species associated both with glaciated and unglaciated areas
notes: Area still being developed into public-access park, but there are couple of rustic trails as well as a board with updates on the plans to add features and such.

gen_desc: Small hamlet southwest of Madison, at the beginning of the "driftless" area.
ecology: Nice road cuts in Cambrian sandstone scattered around small highways and county roads.
species: Lichen are numerous on the sandstone road cuts.

gen_desc: Located along the Dell Creek In Sauk County, near Wisconsin Dells, and consisting of several non-contiguous parcels of land.
ecology: Mostly pine-oak forest, some marshland and grassland.
species: Typical species of mushrooms and lichens thriving on sandy semi-open areas.
notes: Free public access.

gen_desc: Located along the most picturesque part of Wisconsin River, with large stretch of the riverbank protected along this property. Beautiful oasis of calm in the very busy tourist area around Wisconsin Dells.
ecology: Word "Dells" comes from the French word "Dalles", which means river rapids in the deep gorge. The gorge is made of Cambrian Sandstone that is over 500 million years old, and Wisconsin River rushes through it, creating canyons 100 feet deep or more.
species: The area offers variety of exposures and habitats, from deep canyons with water seeping through  the rock to an upland dry forests. Lichens and mushrooms thrive here. Plants of note include Cliff cudweed (Pseudognaphalium saxicola) which is found at only tow places on earth - here and at Kickapoo River Valley.
notes: Several scattered access points, very few developed trails to preserve the pristine beauty of the place. See reference below for the places to park. No parking fees.

gen_desc: Located very near the southern shore of Lake Superior, in Ashland county, Wisconsin.
ecology: The park surrounds the area where Bad River cuts through different geological formations from different Eons of Earth formation. Just along the short stretch of the river present red lavas, black lavas, conglomerate, sandstone, black shale and red clay.
species: Moisture and mist from the numerous falls and rapids in the park produce environment rich with mushrooms and lichen species.
notes: Wisconsin State Parks sticker is required.

gen_desc: A nature preserve in the Fox Valley
ecology: One all cedar swamp with a few open prairies, the center was hit by a tornado changing much of the environment. Still some remnants of the cedar swamp still remain.
??Picea sitchensis??:http://eol.org/pages/1033696 (Sitka Spruce) forest.

gen_desc: University Forest Conservation Area is in Wayne and Butler counties. The area is located near the south side of Lake Wappapello and is approximately 10 miles north of Poplar Bluff. Visitors can acess the area from Routes W, KK, and T in Butler County and Highway 172 and Route W in Wayne County.

id: \n  This 7,149-acre area was originally endowed to the University of Missouri by the federal government as part of the Agriculture College Act of 1862. The School of Forestry, Fisheries and Wildlife took responsibility for the area in the early 1900s and in 1946 began managing the area for research and as a forestry summer camp. The Conservation Department acquired the area in 1988 for the purposes of continuing forest research, creating forest products, woodland related recreation opportunities for the public, and to demonstrate the effects of forest management.
location_id: The area primarily consists of oak-hickory forest with a scattering of shortleaf pine forest. Tree species include black oak, scarlet oak, hickory, maple, and dogwood. The forest provides habitat for deer, turkey, pileated woodpeckers, squirrels, and other typical Ozark wildlife.

gen_desc: Narrow strip of prairies and sand dunes along the Lake Michigan just south of Kenosha, WI and just north of Illinois border.
ecology: Majority of parcels are covered by different types of prairie. Northern part is called Kenosha Sand Dunes.
species: Sand dunes and forested areas in between are interesting from the standpoint of mushrooms and lichens.
notes: The parcels of prairies and dunes are scattered among residential blocks, and are intermixed with them. Multiple small parking areas are available along the road. Access to dunes is from Kenosha's Southport Park just north of the parcel. Chiwaukee Prairie is recognized as National Natural Landmark by the National Park Service.

gen_desc: Parcel of deep woods in the busy Milwaukee County, WI.
ecology: Tow forest types - upland and lowland - separated by a small creek. Unusual species include American Beech which is out of its range here.
species: Lots of fallen tree logs and rotting wood creates many opportunities for mushrooms and other fungi.
notes: Free access. The parcel is a part of Milwaukee County Parks System.

gen_desc: Small local natural landmark hidden in a plain sight along the rural road in Sauk County, WI
ecology: The landmark is part of the sandstone outcrop along the road. Sandstone boulders have both southern and northern exposure.
species: The sandstone boulders and outcrops harbor pretty rich lichen flora, including some unusual stuff.
notes: Watch for the small sign on the pole along the road to spot the location.

gen_desc: Southcentral Wisconsin. Located in the middle of Baraboo Hills.
ecology: Baraboo Range is composed of Baraboo quartzite and believed to be 1.6 billion years old - some of the oldest rocks in America. Having been on the bottom of the sea, with former sandstone metamorphosed into quartzite, the area eventually heaved upwards forming 500-foot bluffs. The lake was created when the glacier moraine blocked the river flow, trapping the water behind.
species: The park is an Ice Age Reserve and hosts tremendous number of rare species of plants and animals. Various environments, including but not limited to cool canyons and exposed sun-backed cliffs harbor wildlife not typical for this latitude.
notes: The park is the third oldest State Park in Wisconsin. It's visited by more than a million people every year, yet has corners where you can get lost for few hours. Wisconsin Parking sticker is required.

gen_desc: Along the Wisconsin River, Part of Lower Wisconsin State Riverway.
ecology: One of the numerous sloughs along Wisconsin River.
species: My interest there involved mostly rocks lining rustic parking lots around the area. Mostly Dolomite, with typical Dolomite dwelling lichen species.
notes: Area is accessible via multiple parking spots along the river, mostly used for launching boats and canoes.

gen_desc: Located in the bluffs overlooking Wisconsin River on its southern bank, just outside of Boscobel, Wisconsin.
ecology: The hills are steep walls of the gorge cut in dolomite by Wisconsin River over the eons. Most are heavily forested, with some clearings and goat prairies abound.
species: Goat prairies have many dolomite outcrops and broken off rocks, giving a substrate to multiple lichen species typical of such environments.
notes: Small parking area is available just off the local highway (see map at the link in the next box).

gen_desc: County Park located in southwestern Dane County near Mt. Vernon, Wisconsin.
ecology: Wooded hills with trail going around in a loop.
species: Fair number of fallen trees affording substrate to various fungi.
notes: At least two parking lots, free access. Park is also used for horse-riding.

gen_desc: The very tip of Door County Peninsula, jutting into the strait called Death's Door between the peninsula and Washington Island.
ecology: The site includes tall dolomite bluffs - section of Niagara Escarpment, prominent along the length of Door County. Heavily forested with White Cedar and hardwoods, also offers windswept bluffs and a rocky beach.
species: Deep White Cedar woods thrive due to the moisture brought constantly in from Lake Michigan and Green Bay. That in turn allows lichen, mosses and fungi to have a prominent presence on the forest floor.
notes: Door County Park; the access is free. No facilities.

gen_desc: The area is to cover the city of Twin Falls, Idaho and the Snake River Canon adjacent to it.  The area includes the actual Twin Falls and Shoshone Waterfalls.
ecology: Elevation: 3,745ft / 1141m,

gen_desc: public land
ecology: rain forest climate, rocky, coniferous forest, near lake
species: This is not working for me - I just wanted to post a picture of a polypore for identification!
notes: public land

gen_desc: Route 40 entrance - https://www.google.com/maps/place/Gunpowder+Falls+State+Park-+Jones+Road+Area/@39.41361,-76.389301,16z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x0:0x3d5efaa8b8be820e!8m2!3d39.412417!4d-76.3884487?hl=en-US
Located near village of Baileys Harbor on shores of Lake Michigan in Door County, WI
ecology: Contains highly prized wet shore forests consisting of species of fur, white cedar, pines and hardwoods. The forest composition is more typical of the types that start in far north Wisconsin and go into CANADA, but are able to survive this far south because of the cooling and wet effect of the lake. This is just one of the smaller parcels of land preserved in this area, along with Ridges Sanctuary and Toft Point.
species: Lots of lichens more typical of the far north. Also, the species that exist elsewhere in Wisconsin can reach huge sizes in this environment, for example _Ramalina americana_ can reach the size of human palm.
notes: One can park for free in designated areas or along the road, and walk into the site.

gen_desc: Public park for the village of Bailey Harbor in Door County, Wisconsin, on Lake Michigan shore.
ecology: Sandy beach and dunes straddling the Baileys Harbor in Lake Michigan. Across the road from much bigger Ridges Sanctuary.
species: Pine environment on dunes, species typical for such places can be found here.
notes: Free public parking, restrooms. The park is small though, and parking can be limited.

gen_desc: In Door County, Wisconsin, very close to and overlooking Green Bay of Lake Michigan
ecology: Situated on top of, and running down the slope of Niagara Escarpment - dolomite backbone of Door County
species: The inhabitants are typical of the cool locations offered by the Escarpment and also species dwelling on dolomites and limestone. Eight species of orchids are found here, along with federally endangered land snails.
notes: Free parking at designated area. This is also one of the preserves  protected by Door County Land Trust

gen_desc: Located near Berlin, Wisconsin.
ecology: Atypical environment offered by two mound fens composed of peat.
species: Rare and unusual plants present here. Lichen and mushrooms can be found long the edge, where the multiuse trail was built on abandoned railroad tracks.
notes: Free parking area is provided, also used for access to the multiuse trail.

gen_desc: Portage County, Wisconsin.
ecology: One of the swamps surrounding Little Wolf River in Central Wisconsin
species: Both species typical of Northern and Southern Wisconsin can be encountered in this area.
notes: As of this writing, the area around on approaches is devastated by logging, so it's hard to get to the spot through the mess left behind.

gen_desc: This is technically a road cut in Adams County, Wisconsin. One of the smallest SNAs in Wisconsin.
ecology: Officially considered an oak barren, ecologically speaking. Contains some species typical for such environments, including many grasses.
species: _Peltigera didactyla_ lichen is very lush and prominent here; other sand dwelling species present.
notes: Very tiny access point, hard to get to when driving through but good for one car.

gen_desc: Located within bigger Deansville Wildlife Area in Dane County, Wisconsin.
ecology: Marshes, fens and wetlands mostly, with some forests mixed in.
species: Anything typical for this part of state, mostly in the woods abutting wetlands.
notes: Many parking spots in the Deansville Wildlife area around the Fen from wich it can be accessed on foot.

gen_desc: Small town park near the river.
ecology: Vegetation typical of this part of Wisconsin, with some effect from the river and nearby dam producing more moisture than usual.
species: Rocks lining parking lot have some lichen species grow on them. Also _Peltigera_ lichen and others dwell on steep slopes descending toward the water edge.
notes: Free parking, public picnic shelter.

gen_desc: School forest area that includes the Point Beach Segment of the Ice Age Trail. Includes swampland, dunes and pine forest.
ecology: Includes swampland, dunes, pine forest and fields
notes: Private except for the ice age trail segment

gen_desc: bq. Located 70 miles southeast of Portland and 65 miles east of Salem, the 36,731 acre Bull of the Woods Wilderness is relatively isolated. Steep ridges are deeply cut by a number of streams including the headwaters of the Collawash, Breitenbush, and Little North Santiam Rivers. The slopes of the numerous peaks are steep, with lower inclines ranging from 30 to 60 degrees and upper inclines from 60 to 90 degrees.

id: \nVegetation changes from old-growth Douglas-fir/western hemlock to sparse sub-alpine forests. About a dozen lakes provide opportunities for fishing. The lakes are scattered throughout the Wilderness, accessible by trail but separated by high ridges.

\nAt 5,523 feet, Bull of the Woods Peak marks the hub of a relatively challenging 75-mile trail system, with several longer or shorter loop opportunities. A historic fire lookout at the summit on Bull of the Woods Peak provides a view of the surrounding area on a clear day.  Traveling through this area you may come across relics of past mining activity from as early as the 1880’s.

ecology: Conifer forest. Dominant species: "??Pseudotsuga menziesii??":http://eol.org/pages/1061712 (Douglas-fir), "??Tsuga heterophylla??":http://eol.org/pages/1033656 (Western Hemlock), "??Thuja plicata??":http://eol.org/pages/1034889 (Western Redcedar)

gen_desc: CYO Youth Camp in Occidental
Community located on the Northwest side of the city of Pensacola in Escambia county, Florida.
ecology: Subtropical climate, Sandy loom,  mixed deciduous woods and pine lands, coastal scrub lands.

gen_desc: Ensley is a community located in Escambia county, Florida . Located North of the city of Pensacola.
ecology: Suburban, USDA  zone 9, temperature ranges between 25f to 95f. Humid. Sandy loom and clay. Primarily oak and pine.
notes: Drive North from Pensacola on hwy. 29 for approximately 5 miles.

gen_desc: Due west of Hollywood Florida.
ecology: Reclaimed everglades , suburbs.

gen_desc: In Oconto Co., approximately 2 miles East of Mountain, WI.  The SNA encompasses about 1000 acres, North and South of County Highway W where it crosses Baldwin Creek.
ecology: Primarily mixed conifer-hardwood forest (oak, maple, pine), with areas of exposed igneous bedrock and associated talus slopes.
species: The site contains a diverse lichen and bryophyte flora, as well as many uncommon/rare plants, such as Purple Clematis, Indian Cucumber Root, and White Adders Mouth.
notes: The entire 1006 acres is open to public use, and is entirely within the Chequamegon-Nicolet National Forest.
refs: Developed access to this site is fairly primitive.  The primary areas of the exposed bedrock are immediately north and south of CTH W, east of Baldwin Cr.  A minimally-developed trail exists that can be accessed from Bear Paw Rd., approximately 1 mile east of CTH W.  From here, the trail heads in a northerly direction, through one area of exposed bedrock, crosses CTH W, and leads you to another area of exposed bedrock.  It is also possible to access the site from the north, from Sunrise Lake Rd., using a primitive road just W of Macauley Creek.

gen_desc: Located off Greek Cemetery rd, Eleanor, Alabama.
ecology: Subtropical, pine plantation, oak hammocks.  Borders pasture land.
species: White rot seemed prevalent on a large percentage of the white oaks. Inonotus are common.
notes: This is a public location,  foot traffic only. Locals will investigate anyone who stops on Greek Cemetery rd. This is due to someone listing the pastures as a good cubensis spot. You will be charged with trespassing if you enter any of the surrounding properties.

gen_desc: almost 90,000 acres of forested mountains and grasslands at the junction of the Cascade Range and the Siskiyou Mountains in southern Oregon and northern California
ecology: From mixed conifers to oak woodlands and grasslands, semi-arid mediterranean climate

gen_desc: In NW Jefferson Co., WI, roughly 2 mi. due SW from downtown Lake Mills.
ecology: Aside from the lake itself, the majority of the habitat consists of tamarack and shrub swamp, with a few upland "islands" of oak-dominated hardwoods. The swampy areas are noted for having a particularly abundant population of poison sumac.  Also, the swamp becomes very quicksand-like near the edge of the lake, so tread with caution.  A nearly buried boat trailer at the end of the trail by the lakeshore serves as a warning to all.
notes: This area is state-owned land, a designated natural area.  A parking area exists at the dead-end of Bean Lake Rd.  From there, a trail heads north, then east, to a very primitive "landing" on the west lakeshore.  Near the lakeshore, another trail branches off to the north, across the top of an "island" of upland hardwoods.  A second, less-used trail also starts at the parking area, heading east, and leading to the swamp, SW of the lake.

id: \nThe upland hardwood islands on the northeast side of the lake are an archaeological site (Bean Lake Islands Archaeological District).  The prominent feature is a series of concentric trenches dug out by Native Americans.  While the trenches are still noticeable, the average person without any prior knowledge would likely not recognize anything out of the ordinary.  Attempting to visit these islands when the ground is not frozen is not recommended.
location_id: http://dnr.wi.gov/topic/Lands/naturalareas/index.asp?SNA=111

gen_desc: In Jefferson Co., WI, approx. 5 miles north of Lake Mills, and 5 miles ESE of Waterloo.
ecology: A small, 25-acre unplowed remnant of what was historically a large wet prairie along the Crawfish River in this area.
species: There are some state and federally-listed plant species present.
notes: Access is via a dirt farm lane that heads east of CTH G (Look for fire number N8696).  A small parking area is present at the SW corner of the prairie.

id: \nThere are no maintained trails at this site, although a foot path typically is noticeable due to the conservation-related work that occurs here.
location_id: http://dnr.wi.gov/topic/Lands/naturalareas/index.asp?SNA=168

gen_desc: Wild and Scenic Clackamas River.
ecology: old growth forest of Douglas Fir, cedar and hemlock

gen_desc: Mountain pass along highway 299 east of Redding. Elevation around 3000 feet.
ecology: Mixture of pine, fir, and hardwoods.
notes: It seems like it is mostly private property but there are some pull outs from the highway that don't have any signs posted.

gen_desc: Located North of U.S Hwy 90 Along the Perdido River in Escambia county Florida.  There is a public boat ramp and a variety of habitats.
ecology: Temperate, warm, humid, long summer days and short winter. Average rain fall is approximately 62" a year on average.

id: \nOak hammocks, mixed woods,  wire grass prairie,  flood plains. Pitcher plant habitat, loblolly and longleaf pine.
location_id: Macrocybe Titans,  various Ganoderma species, carnivorous plants,  wild turkey, bald eagles,  wild hogs, white tail deer, Eastern diamond back rattle snake.
source_type: Public access from sunrise to sunset.  Boat ramp. Entrance on Hwy 90 across from the Florida weigh station or at the western end of Frank Reeder rd. Excellent hiking and horse back riding.

gen_desc: Located North of U.S Hwy 90 Along the Perdido River in Escambia county Florida.  There is a public boat ramp and a variety of habitats.
ecology: Temperate, warm, humid, long summer days and short winter. Average rain fall is approximately 62" a year on average.

gen_desc: Located in the Western panhandle of Florida.  It is seperated grom Alabama by the perdido river to the West. Pensacola is the cradle of naval aviation, the home of the Blue Angels.

location_id: Temperate, warm, humid, long summer days and short winter. Average rain fall is approximately 62" a year on average.
source_name: Fort pickens on Santa Rosa island and Fort Barrancas on Naval Air Station Pensacola are must sees.

gen_desc: Stream of snow melt forms a nice waterfall running down from the high Sierra Nevada through gold country north of Sierraville.
ecology: Wet cool spring, warm dry summer, cool dry fall, cold snowy winter. Lots of granite. Mixed conifer forest. Ponderosa pine, fir, and cedar are common.
notes: National forest, public access, free parking in lot, paved path to the falls.

ecology: Mesic to wet and boggy mature hemlock forest
notes: According to the Wisconsin DNR website, the two easternmost 80 acre rectangular tracts are the best areas to visit. There is a parking lot just off of County Highway G on Zimmer Rd. from where one can walk N to get to the northwestern most tract. The hemlocks are tall, the forest canopy closed, with very little growth in the understory – the forest is completely traversable – and a greater diversity of mushrooms than I have ever seen at once. It was difficult to walk without stepping on a giant Russula or Amanita, or some other coral, hydnoid, or boletoid mushroom. It was one of the most beautiful forests I have seen. The collection of edible fungi is allowed on Wisconsin State Natural Area land.

gen_desc: Located in the central sands region of Wisconsin, Hancock Agricultural Research Station consists of very sandy soils and generally flat terrain.
notes: Hancock Agricultural Research Station is owned and operated by the University of Wisconsin-Madison. There is a horticultural garden open to the public, but otherwise the research station is only open to people who are affiliated with UW-Madison.

gen_desc: coastal forest
ecology: Abies balsamea, betula
species: Cantharellus enelensis, Hynum repandum, Amanita amerirubescens, Harrya chromapes
notes: borders on the national park

Mecan River Fishery Area consists of disconnected but widespread parcels of land owned by the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources. Most areas are accessible to the public at all times of the year. Foraging for wild edibles is permitted. Find more information on the DNR Mecan River Fishery Area "website":https://dnr.wi.gov/topic/lands/fisheriesareas/1620mecanriver.html, and make sure to check out their "map":https://dnr.wi.gov/maps/FM/NER/1620mecanriverboth.pdf as these public lands are not visible in Google Maps.
refs: DNR Fisheries Areas: Mecan River Fishery Area:https://dnr.wi.gov/topic/lands/fisheriesareas/1620mecanriver.html

notes: Crum Woods is private land owned by Swarthmore College. Visitors are welcome, but should stay on trail and not remove material from the woods. Many students carry out research here and any equipment should not be disturbed.

University of Wisconsin-Madison owns and operates Rhinelander Agricultural Research Station. A permit is required to enter and sample at the research station. Visitors should always check in with the main office to see if there have been recent sprayings of agrochemicals.

gen_desc: Tyrone is a town located in West Central Georgia about 30 miles southwest of Atlanta in northwestern Fayette County. It is bordered by Sharpsburg to the west, Palmetto to the northwest, Fairburn to the north, Fayetteville to the east, and Peachtree city to the south.

id: \nIt is located in the headwaters of the Flint River Basin. The western border of the town (and Fayette County) is Line Creek, and Flat Creek flows through central Tyrone.
location_id: The climate is a subtropical humid climate with warm humid summers and mild winters.

id: \nThe soils are generally the heavy clay typical of much of the state of Georgia.
\nThe predominate tree cover is Loblolly Pine, with many species of Oak, Red Maple, Sweetgum, Dogwoods, and Tulip Poplar making up the bulk of the remainder.

\nMuch of the landscape is suburban or rural, as Tyrone is largely a commuter town based around the southern Atlanta metropolitan area's Healthcare system and Hartsfield Jackson International Airport. However, film production is ramping up as of the late 2010s, with many areas on the Northside dedicated to the metro Atlanta film industry.

gen_desc: Near the intersection of Highway 141 and Bowles Ave.
ecology: Hospital grounds with parking lot and mulch around trees.
notes: A public area.

gen_desc: Located in midst of the hills lining Wisconsin River not too far from Wisconsin merging with Mississippi. Part of Lower Wisconsin State Riverway.
ecology: So-called driftless area, steep hills and deep valleys. This particular area sits next to Wisconsin River, getting influenced by that body of water.
species: Dry mesic forest has rich understory and forest floor flora. The place is remote and hard to access except from the water, so many species thrive here undisturbed.
notes: No permits are required, just stamina and patience getting to this place.

gen_desc: Located in former prairie region, currently among the pastures and crops.
ecology: Small patches of preserved prairie and a depression in the ground moraine crating a pond.
species: This is mostly a bird sanctuary and rich aquatic environment. The area is of no consequence to mushroom lovers, except there are some glacial boulders strewn around that have some decent lichens on them.
notes: Public access, small parking areas scattered around.

gen_desc: Located within Badfish Creek Wildlife Area.
ecology: Mostly wetlands with some patches of woods scattered.
species: Typical wet prairie plant species, and birds and animals associated with wet prairies. Not much in a way of mushrooms, but wooded area harbor number of species, due to the wetness of the location.
notes: Public access.

gen_desc: Former prairie parts of the state of Wisconsin. Currently scattered among pastures and crops.
ecology: Rich prairie remnants.
species: Many rare or declining prairie plants; birds associated with such environments as well. Of low consequence to mushroom lovers. Some boulders scattered around with lichens on them, also patches of oak and other woodlands here and there.
notes: Public access. Parking areas scattered around to correspond with separated (not contiguous) patches of prairie.

gen_desc: Deep within Rusk County Forest, Wisconsin.
ecology: This is unique feature - only 3 are known from Wisconsin. Felsenmeer is translated as a "sea of rocks". These felsenmeers were created by combination of the glacier activity during an Ice Age and subsequent frost action that lead to quartzite's cleaving and creating rock taluses in the middle of the woods.
species: Talus slopes are rich in lichen, including more northern species, thanks to cold air emanating from between the rocks and creating tundra-like environment. Woods are typical northwoods rich with all kinds of mushrooms.
notes: Public access. Area is very remote and some places are very hard to reach. Nothing is marked on the ground - no trail markings whatsoever, no indication you're at the right spot or even on public property, no maps at the trailheads, even small roads' names aren't posted. It's recommended to contact Rusk County forestry department for maps before going into these woods.

gen_desc: Along Wisconsin River, with Lower Wisconsin State Riverway.
ecology: Typical riverside barrens, with oak and pine and sandy lichen-covered floor.
species: Many lichen species typical of such environments, like _Cladonia_. Occasional sand-loving mushrooms can be found as well.
notes: Public access

gen_desc: Located within Cadiz Springs State Recreation Area.
ecology: Mostly sloping wooded area, with small sandstone ravine. Rich oak woods.
species: Number of mushroom species associated with oak woods.
notes: Public access. But State Parks sticker is required since this is part of the State Recreation Area (you have to drive to the Recreation area itself to buy the sticker).

gen_desc: East side of Oregon coastal range, west of _location Corvallis, Benton Co., Oregon_
ecology: Mixed coastal conifer forest, with Special Botanical Area, open meadows and large "??Abies procera??":http://eol.org/pages/1033079 (Noble Fir) forest near top.

source_type: Patchwork of federal (National Forest, BLM), state, and private land. Largest portion is within the Siuslaw National Forest.

gen_desc: Located along the Charles River and Indian Brook in Natick, MA.  This is an Audubon sanctuary.

location_id: Varied, often moist habitats.  Excellent seasonal diversity.
source_name: This is a Mass Audubon Sanctuary; a fee or pass is required.
gen_desc: https://www.massaudubon.org/get-outdoors/wildlife-sanctuaries/broadmoor
This location is the area bounded on the North and East by US 26, on the West by NF Road 2656, and on the South by the northern end of Mud Creek Ridge.
ecology: Older meadow which is filling in with mixed forest, largely conifer.
refs: Zigzag Ranger District Map, Oregon (2002), publish by Mt. Hood National Forest

gen_desc: This is located in mid-state, on the border between southern prairie-like part of the state, and northern part that's called "North Woods". But it doesn't mean that northern part is all woods, or that southern part is not forested.
ecology: This particular location is surrounded by water on three sides, being on a strip of land jutting deep into the lake. This creates environment that is moister than normal and promotes fungi growth in what otherwise would be considered dry mesic forest. Parts of old growth forest provide many rotting trees and logs with plenty of microhabitats for mushrooms.
species: This location is known for its rich spring ephemeral flora.
notes: Location is open to the public ad has free access.

gen_desc: Located on the steep bluff slope facing Mississippi River in Southwest Wisconsin.
ecology: Western exposure to the Mississippi-influenced microclimate and prevailing winds from the West. Very steep slope, almost impossible to walk, on a dolomite/sandstone bluff side. Also has what's called algific talus slope - those face the opposite (Eastern) direction and are known for trapping ice for a long time and producing cold air drafts, supporting plant communities in South Wisconsin that are more typical on much more Northern climate.
species: This location has some of the rarest snails in the state, including one that was recently found, that was considered extinct and was known previously only from fossils.
notes: Location can be accessed only from the road that runs through it - Dugway Rd. From there, one has to hike uphill. There seems to be no trails or any other, easier access to the site.

gen_desc: Part of Cherney Maribel County Park, on West Twin River in Manitowoc County
ecology: The site contains 50 foot dolomite bluff, and a river just down slope, creating microclimate great for fungi and lichens. Also has shallow caves in the dolomite bluff.
species: American beech grows here. Birds more common up north can be found on site.
notes: Location is open to public and free.

gen_desc: Part of an extensive system of wetlands located east of Madison, feeding Yahara River.
ecology: Wetlands, ponds and marshes, interspersed with patches of woods on hillocks rising above the marsh.
species: Area supports number of plants and is a paradise for bird-watchers. Mushroom-wise there are pockets of land that are pretty wet throughout the season, and can host various mushrooms.
notes: Free and open to the public

gen_desc: Few miles south of Richland Center, Richland Co, Wisconsin, USA
ecology: Forested hills and a creek valley. Also includes a pine plantation, intersperced with other conifers like tamarack.
species: Hills and valleys provide different exposures and elevations within the forest. Plenty of downed trees and lots of different habitats for fungi.
notes: Free access, two parking lots within the forest.

gen_desc: Within Mud Lake Wildlife Area, Dodge County, Wisconsin.
ecology: Mostly marshlands and wetlands. Crawfish River is a primary waterway through.
species: Not overall a prime spot for mushrooms, but patches of woods here and there may offer some fungi.
notes: Free access.

gen_desc: Within Mud Lake Wildlife Area in Dodge County, Wisconsin, USA
ecology: Marshlands with small oak woods on the border.
species: Mostly open oak woodland, not very interesting from mushroom standpoint, but oaks have a tendency to attract fungi so potentially some can be found here.
notes: Free access

gen_desc: This location is right outside of the city of Reedsburg in Sauk County, Wisconsin.
ecology: The part of the location of interest is a wet forest, turning to marshland in some places, with locations that have a higher ground. Major portion of this site is a prairie known historically for being the last stronghold of a Prairie Chicken in Sauk County.
species: Wet forest supports lots of mushrooms.
notes: Free public access.

gen_desc: Located in Walworth County, Wisconsin, within Kettle Moraine State Forest.
ecology: Part of the Ice Age legacy of Wisconsin - Kettle Moraine is an area where two glacier lobes met and pushed against one another during Ice Age. Area is interspersed with kettles and moraines and other glacier features. This particular site has mounds that started forming thousands of years ago, and have unique vegetation.
species: From mushroom standpoint, this site has forested area with wet mixed forest rich with mushrooms.
notes: Public access. DNR sticker may be required if parking on State Forest lots and inner roads.

gen_desc: Part of the Keweenaw Peninsula of the Upper Michigan (UP), Copper Harbor is one of the shelter locations on otherwise exposed north-western side of the Peninsula. This location is at the very tip of the Peninsula jutting into the Lake Superior.
ecology: North-west exposure, shore of Lake Superior. Hard and cold climate, moderated somewhat by the lake. Shore locations are constantly wet from the lake breeze and wave action. Most of the shoreline is composed of Conglomerate rock.
species: The location is a paradise for lichens, with hundreds of species dwelling on conglomerate, with nooks and crannies having different exposures, microclimates and lighting. There are locations where rocks are almost completely covered by lichens, with rock surface barely visible.
notes: Many sites along the shore are private, but small public parks and other free public access exist along the shore.

gen_desc: Part of much bigger Deer Creek State Wildlife Area in Outagamie County, Wisconsin.
ecology: Tamarack marsh, wetlands and upland woods.
species: Many mushrooms, given the mixed conifer-hardwood nature of the forest and plenty of moisture.
notes: Free public access.

gen_desc: Rocky gorge bisected by the Eau Claire River in Marathon County, Wisconsin, east of Wausau. River gorge is a State Natural Area (described in separate entry)
ecology: Mixed conifer-birch forest with some other hardwoods mixed in. Plenty of wet locations and depressions, also small hillocks offering wide variety of exposures and microclimates.
species: From mushroom stand point, this is one of the richest types of forest that exist in the state. The location harbors staggering number of species of ground-dwelling mushrooms (as opposed to those that grow on logs, trees etc.)
notes: Free public access; numerous parking points available.

gen_desc: Within bigger Dells of Eau Claire County Park, Marathon County, Wisconsin.
ecology: The State Natural Area, being part of the County Park, covers mostly the rocky gorge composed of the rhyolite, river itself and the areas along the riverbank. Hemlock forest with Canada Yew, birch and maple.
species: Rocks covered by lichen benefiting from the mist coming from the river gorge. Likewise mushrooms on the shore benefit from the plenty of moisture and wealth of microhabitats.
notes: Free public access.

gen_desc: Within Rusk County Forest.
ecology: Rusk County Forest is an extensive forested expanse with various features. Devil's Kettle is of interest as a geological feature, part of the small gorge within the woods.
species: Has typical fungal habitats and species typical elsewhere in the County Forest.
notes: Free public access, very difficult to find due to a lack of an official website and lack of any signage on the ground. Do Internet search or stop at Ladysmith Chamber of Commerce to get a crude map.

gen_desc: Within Nelson Dewey State Park on the banks of Mississippi River on Wisconsin side.

location_id: Top of the bluff, windswept dry "goat prairie" with western exposure towards Mississippi. Dolomite bluffs with numerous crevices and dolomite blocks strewn around provide multitude of habitats for lichens, soil crusts and other bryophytes.
source_type: Numerous rare plants - both grasses and forbs. Rich lichen communities, with mostly crustose but also some foliose species.
source_name: Need DNR annual or daily sticker purchased in order to access the State Park, and SNA within it.
gen_desc: https://dnr.wi.gov/topic/Lands/naturalareas/index.asp?SNA=10
Community on the shores of Lake Superior in Keweenaw Peninsula, Michigan.
ecology: Northwestern exposure to the Lake Superior, with prevailing winds from North-West. Rocky shores composed mostly of Conglomerate Rock.
species: Conglomerate rock supports staggering number of lichen species, helped by the mist and moisture coming from the wave breaks and lake in general.
notes: Public access spots are scattered along the shoreline; otherwise most of the shoreline is taken over by private owners.

gen_desc: Sandstone bluff (butte) typical of the ones in the otherwise flat Adams County, Wisconsin. Also called Easton Mound.
ecology: Sandstone bluff jutting up from the flatlands. Sides covered by hardwood forest, with pines on top of the bluff, typical for such buttes in the area.
species: Sandstones with different exposures provide rich habitat for different species of lichens.
notes: Free access, but difficult to find. One needs to seek a trail access off 11th Dr. Trail leads to the top of the bluff.

gen_desc: Community in Door County, Wisconsin, on the western side of the Dorr Peninsula.
ecology: North-western exposure to the Lake Michigan (actually Green Bay). Bedrock is dolomite of the Niagara Escarpment that comes out to the surface in many places.
species: Dolomite cliffs offer rich habitats for lichens, where exposed and accessible by public.
notes: One needs to seek public access to the rocky shores, like town beaches and such.

gen_desc: Close to northern tip of the Door Peninsula, Door County, Wisconsin.
ecology: On top of Niagara Escarpment - Dolomite bedrock formation stretching from New York to Wisconsin. his park has northwestern exposure to the Lake Michigan (Green Bay).
species: White Cedar forest with some hardwoods provides shelter to rare species of animals and plants, like some relict land snails. Exposed dolomite is good place to look for lichens, and the trees are also rich with them, and there are different mushrooms found in the wooded areas.
notes: Free public access. No trails in the park, so it's not easy to browse around given the steep topography.

gen_desc: Within the community of Ephraim in Door County, Wisconsin.
ecology: Includes different types of forest, part of Niagara Escarpment, wetlands.
species: Dolomite of Niagara Escarpment is good place to look for lichens. Also lichens on trees. Mushrooms can be found throughout the forest.
notes: Part of the Door County Land Trust network of protected preserves. Free public access.

gen_desc: Within the community of Ephraim in Door County, Wisconsin.
ecology: Wetlands and wet woods. This site is a reclaimed logging location.
species: Typical wetland and forest species found in this portion of the Door County. Abundance of water under the tree canopy provides rich habitats for mushrooms.
notes: Free access from the main road (well-marked entrance and parking lot). However, village of Ephraim doesn't seem to maintain the site, so many wooden bridges on the looping trail are collapsed or on disrepair.

gen_desc: In Monroe County, Wisconsin.
ecology: Majority of the site is a steep hill slope with hardwood forest on it.
species: Wooded slopes provide a good opportunity for mushrooms. Also a parking lot by the creek, with many boulders that offer habitat to various lichens. Location supports some rare forbs.
notes: Free public access.

gen_desc: Part of Lower Wisconsin State Riverway in Sauk County, Wisconsin.
ecology: Sandy barrens and mixed pine-oak woods. Very dry location.
species: Many lichens from the genus Cladonia that thrive on the sandy soils.
notes: Free public access.

gen_desc: Preserve straddles the channel between Lac La Belle and Bete Grise Bay of Lake Michigan, on the Keweenaw Peninsula of Upper Michigan (UP)
ecology: Mostly wetlands along Lake Superior shore; includes shoreline.
species: Numerous endemic species of lichen, and non-lichen flora and fauna as well
notes: Access free and public.

gen_desc: At the tip of Keweenaw Peninsula of the Upper Michigan (UP).
ecology: Marine climate due to being surrounded by Lake Superior, at the very narrow tip of peninsula.
species: Plenty of tree-dwelling lichen species around the park and nearby.
notes: Parking fee is required to park on several available parking spots.

gen_desc: In Marquette County, Wisconsin
ecology: Large wetland complex, part of even larger French Creek Wildlife Area.
species: Mostly wetland species of plants; hard to assess lichen and mushroom flora due to difficulties accessing the site (wet marshland and bogs).
notes: Free public access

gen_desc: Preserve near Waterloo, in Jefferson County of Wisconsin. Known better for its Native American Mounds.
ecology: Glacial hill elevated over the surrounding plain and wetlands.
species: Typical upland woodland species that are found in this region.
notes: Free public access; multiple walking trails.

gen_desc: Bluffs along the Mississippi River.
ecology: Includes so-called "goat prairies" and also wooded slopes descending down towards the Mississippi River.
species: This is a northernmost point of Chinquapin Oak distribution. Goat prairies are known for harboring rare and overlooked species of lichen, benefiting from the close proximity to the river and plenty of sun exposure.
notes: Free access, parking along the road (no dedicated parking).

gen_desc: Small path along the American River.
ecology: Cottonwood trees grow on the banks of the river. There is a landfill nearby.
notes: Public park

gen_desc: The *United Nations Disengagement Observer Force (UNDOF)* was established by United Nations Security Council Resolution 350 on 31 May 1974, to implement Resolution 338 (1973) which called for an immediate ceasefire and implementation of United Nations Security Council Resolution 242.

id: \nThe resolution was passed on the same day the Agreement on Disengagement was signed between Israeli and Syrian forces on the Golan Heights, finally establishing a ceasefire to end the 1973 Yom Kippur War.

\nThe Force has since performed its functions with the full cooperation of both sides. The mandate of UNDOF has been renewed every six months since 1974 (most recently until 31 December 2018). UNTSO (United Nations Truce Supervision Organization) and UNDOF are operating in the zone and continue to supervise the ceasefire. Before the Syrian Civil War, the situation in the Israel-Syria ceasefire line had remained quiet and there had been no serious incidents.

\nDuring the *Syrian Civil War*, the buffer zone between Israeli and Syrian forces became a scene of the Quneitra clashes, forcing many UN observer forces to reconsider their mission due to safety issues. The fighting between Syrian Army and Syrian Opposition came to international attention when on March 2013, the al-Qaeda affiliated group Al-Nusra Front took hostage 21 Fijian UN personnel, who had been a part of the UN Disengagement Observer Force in the neutral buffer zone between Syria and Israeli-occupied territory. According to a UN official, they were taken hostage near Observation Post 58, which had sustained damage and was evacuated the previous weekend, following heavy combat in close proximity at Al Jamla. The UN personnel were later released with Jordanian mediation.

gen_desc: Soils: In this overall region, geology tends to be of a calcareous base, mostly dolomite and calcite. The soils are generally either sandy or clayey.

id: \nClimate: Most of the year the weather is sunny, with temperatures reaching averages of around 30ºC+ in the summer and 14ºC in the winter. Summers are very dry while winters are very moist.

\nFruiting seasons: There are two main fruiting seasons. The main one tends to peak in mid or end of November, while there is a generally weaker season in the spring, peaking  between March and April.
location_id: This area is very rich in the sense that it has several habitats.

id: \nMostly sandy, it has relatively large areas of Pinus pinaster, Pinus pinea and Quercus suber. Occasionaly one can find Q. faginea. Other Quercus species, as Q. lusitanica and Q. coccifera are scattared all over. Several Cistus species are abundant and scattared.
\nThe area is hilly surrounded by one main water stream, providing moisture in the winter.
location_id: Several collybioide species close to the fetid Gymnopus

gen_desc: Soils: In this overall region, geology tends to be of a calcareous base, mostly dolomite and calcite. The soils are generally either sandy or clayey.

id: \nClimate: Most of the year the weather is sunny, with temperatures reaching averages of around 30ºC+ in the summer and 14ºC in the winter. Summers are very dry while winters are very moist.
\nFruiting seasons: There are two main fruiting seasons. The main one tends to peak in mid or end of November, while there is a generally weaker season in the spring, peaking between March and April.
location_id: Very sandy area with large Pinus pinea forest. Many openings too. There's a sea lagoon limiting it with a rich fauna. Occasional forest fires close by.

gen_desc: *Mawsynram*, India, located in the Meghalaya State, receives the highest rainfall in India. The large volume of rain is caused by the Himalayas Ranges blocking heavy clouds' escape to the North.

id: \nMawsynram is reportedly the wettest place on Earth, with an average annual rainfall of 11,872 millimetres (467.362 in), but that claim is disputed by Lloró, Colombia, which reported an average yearly rainfall of 12,717 millimetres (500.7 in) between 1952 and 1989 and López de Micay, also in Colombia, which reported 12,892 mm (507.6 in) per year between 1960 and 2012.

\nAccording to the Guinness Book of World Records, Mawsynram received 26,000 millimetres (1,000 in) of rainfall in 1985. Mawsynram received 745.2 mm of rainfall on August 19 of 2015, probably the highest rainfall received by the town to date.
gen_desc: https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/the-ten-wettest-places-in-the-world.html
Gays Mills is a village in southwestern Wisconsin, in so-called Driftless Area, along the Kickapoo River.
ecology: There are sandstone outcrops in road-cuts around the place, home to multiple lichen species. Also old wooden fences along the roads, home to corticolous lichen.
notes: Parking along the roads and at outlooks.

gen_desc: Also known as “Pinhal d’El-Rei” or “Mata Nacional de Leiria”. It is an artificial Pinus pinaster monoculture, planted and expanded between 1223 and 1325 by Sancho II, Dinis I and Sancho III, kings of Portugal, with the goal of protecting the nearby farmlands and inhabitations from the winds and advancing dunes brought from the ocean side. It had a central role in the discoveries and exploration of new continents by portuguese and other europeans, from where wood and resin was extracted to build caravels and other ships. Recent forest fires has cleared most of the area from pine, wherein many locals are promoting the replantation of the original forest prior the 13th and 14th centuries.
ecology: Sands with Pinus pinaster

gen_desc: One of the most famous nature places within the urban ranges of Jyväskylä city center, in Central Finland.
ecology: Surrounded by lakes, with a hill top in the middle, is a very green and moist area, natural valleys and relatively dense forest areas. Mainly birches, spruces and pines. Finnish bedrock.

gen_desc: Continental United States, Idaho. National region: Pacific North West of United States. State quadrant: South East, Idaho
ecology: North Western Great Basin Desert. High Desert primarily Sagebrush Steppe. Southern Sawtooth Mountain range turning into Cold desert. Geology: once over magma hot spot which is not located under Yellowstone NP due to continental plate drift westward. Snake River Valley.

source_name: A 300 acre park in SE Seattle on the Bailey Peninsula in Lake Washington.
gen_desc: On the one mile long Bailey Peninsula on the western shore of Lake Washington, a large freshwater lake which forms the eastern border of Seattle WA.
ecology: The park is glacial till covered with typical low-elevation forest for the Puget Sound area.

source_name: A 300 acre park in SE Seattle on peninsula in Lake Washington.

gen_desc: Expansive area of marshlands in Marquette County, WI, straddling Mecan River and tributaries.
ecology: Of interest to mushroomers are upland woods within the Wildlife Area, and tamarack groves that are part of the marsh.
species: Various mushrooms species enjoy constantly wet environment.
notes: Open to the public; free parking.

gen_desc: Massive sandstone rock overlooking the Wisconsin River valley near Lake Wisconsin.
ecology: Woods - covered slopes. The south side of the Gibraltar is a sheer rock drop, exposed to winds and erosion. Turkey vultures are nesting in the upper woods. Other raptors enjoy the thermals created by the rock surface.
species: Wooded slopes are good for variety of mushrooms. The exposed rock wall, top of the hill and scattered around boulders are boon for various lichens.
notes: Free public parking - two locations. One is Gibraltar Rock SNA itself, and the other is Ice Age Trail parking lot (Ice Age Trail bisects the site).

gen_desc: Bike trail occupying former rail corridor between Cottage Grove and Waukesha, Wisconsin.
ecology: Former rail corridor, usually has a narrow line of trees on both sides.
species: Mostly lichens on trees that line the trail.
notes: Trail pass is required for bicyclists, but pedestrians are free. Multiple access points in towns and villages along the trail.

gen_desc: County Park in Washington County, WI
ecology: Variety of topography around the lake, on the former interlobate moraine. Mostly hilly with different exposures.
species: Has interesting variety of mushrooms, due to different exposures offered by hills and slopes, and the lake in between. King Bolete has been found here, which is unusual for such a southern location with mostly southern mesic forest on the slopes.
notes: Free parking. Bathrooms are on site.

gen_desc: 20 by 20 ft of tipuwana tipu mulch in a shady area, flat
ecology: Just a bare patch of un used soil in a disturbed urban environment, with mulch from leaves tipus
species: Rare. A mushroom the size of a fist with falls gills or teeth on exterior of mushroom. Stalk is short and non tapering running all the way through the mushroom. The mushroom shows no reproduction organs on inside with a light lavender color to interior and exterior

id: \nMushroom is very solid non viscous and meaty. Smell earthy qnd nutty

location_id: Buisness park

gen_desc: Northern California central valley oak prairie.
ecology: Hot dry summer. Landscaped college campus with lots of native oak trees. Small redwood grove and a variety of other planted conifers.
notes: Parking passes required but it’s a college so it is open to the public.

gen_desc: Located in West Pensacola between Fairfield dr., New warrington rd, Hwy 98 ,  elizsberg, there are several access areas, here are a few: Fairfield drive and Bay Springs drive , Patton drive (3-4 access areas),  Pensacola state college warrington campus on Hwy 98.

id: \nThe Trail is the center of Jones Swamp, Jones swamp is the headwaters of Bayou Chico.
location_id: Swamp, flood plains,  old pine plantation, hardwood hammocks, creek.
source_type: Various species of mushrooms and other fungi, Wood ducks, Great Blue herons, Great Egrets,  Large Sweet bay Magnolias,  Southern Magnolias,  Huckleberry, wild Blueberry,  live oak, water oak, pine trees,  alligators,  beavers,  bass,  bream, black bears,  white tailed deer,  rabbit,  Barn owls.
source_name: Open to the public from sunrise to sunset,  wheelchair friendly (especially if it hasn't raised in a couple days,  most of the Trail is boardwalk but there are a few hard packed sand areas.

gen_desc: In Cle Elum, Washington.
ecology: Lush forest with a few trails that border a river that runs through it. Some areas are dry but the trails that border the river are usually more damp and humid. There are also quite a few areas where there are clearings and charred trees.
species: Have observed Boletaceae, Psathyrella, and Psathyrellaceae Vilgalys.
notes: A good location for hunting if you're in the Kittitas County area.

gen_desc: In Kittitas County, Washington.
ecology: Small town that has large forests, rivers, and a lake. There's also quite a bit of farmland with grazing livestock. Climate differs from dry to humid depending where and when you go.
species: Morels are known to be somewhat common in the area.

id: \nHave observed Panaeolus Semiovatus on the farmland.
location_id: The forests are great for hunting a number of edible mushrooms.

gen_desc: A forest that's located in a desert with a river that runs through. There are a few trails that lead to and border the river, with a decent size water fall.
ecology: Mostly hot and dry, with a few muddy areas next to the river. Surprisingly lush and green foliage considering the climate. There's a few areas that are very rocky.
notes: The trailhead is several miles down Umtanum Road, which is a gravel road. It's a public trail with no permits required.

gen_desc: Small park and forest that boarders the Yakima River. There's a pond in the park as well.
ecology: Usually quite dry, but it has lush foliage and a thick forest. In the park theres lots of green, well-maintained grass.
notes: It's a public park with a portion that closes after 10:00 PM, so make sure to leave before or your car will be locked inside the parking lot overnight.

gen_desc: Small park in Ellensburg that lines some apartments and a small creek.
ecology: Small grassy park with a gravel path that circles it. Theres a few small areas that has a groups of trees lined with patches of wood chips. There's also gravel side-path that leads to a small creek. It's quite dry most of the time, which is usual for Ellensburg.

gen_desc: This is a conservation area created by the adjacent Turnkey Landfill on Rochester Neck Road in Rochester New Hampshire.  It's lower bound is the Isinglass River
ecology: This area was farmland in the early 20th century and has overgrown to mixed conifer and deciduous forest along the banks of the Isinglass River, hard by the Turnkey Landfill.  It provides a variety of terrain from bog to upland.  Several public trails provide easy access.  As the river name implies, there is abundant mica in the granite bedrock which underlies it.  There are many mature and senescent Hemlock and White Pine standing over a maturing hardwood forest.  At the lowest level in the shade of the hardwoods, small white pine are growing which will form the climax forest in a century or so.  Temperatures average below freezing in winter with the first frost from late September to mid October.  It is fairly similar to the College Woods area in Durham, except it sits next to a landfill instead of a university.  The reader is invited draw his or her own conclusions as to which is better.
species: There are interesting coral mushrooms and Clavinopulis to be found.

gen_desc: The Learning Area (LA) of Sítio de Monfurado is a Natura 2000 site at the Central Alentejo Region.
ecology: The landscape character is closely related to the dominant dense Montado, managed extensively in large farm estates, and it is generally a High Nature Value farming system. The Montado is a human shaped ecosystem composed of complementary elements and activities. The open tree cover (Quercus rotundifolia and Quercus suber) provides wood, cork and shelter for the livestock grazing underneath. The undercover is composed of pastures combined with shrubs in varied densities. There are also highly diverse riparian corridors and some Mediterranean temporary ponds. Additionally, smaller areas of small-scale mosaic and traditional olive groves surround the villages.
notes: A lot of it is private, but still many areas to explore freely.

gen_desc: Location is at 1400 feet elevation at the base of forested, north-facing slopes, along the south side of the Trinity River and includes a seasonal creek.
ecology: Climate includes dry and hot summers (to 105oF and prone to drought), with cool, wet, foggy winters that occasionally provide heavy rains, heavy wet snow and/or low temperatures into the teens (oF).  A land of seasonal climate extremes, positioned near the southern border of the Trinity Alps Wilderness between the Sacramento Valley at Redding and the California coast at Arcata/Eureka.  The position of this property provides some evening temperature moderation during hot summer months from downslope and river influences (hence the presence of isolated, island populations of plant species such as Western Red Cedar, ferns, and Fawn Lily).

id: \nContiguous property and public forest includes a mix of Douglas Fir, Western Red Cedar, Ponderosa Pine, Jeffrey Pine, Sugar Pine, Gray Pine, Oregon White Oak, Black Oak, Madrone, Big Leaf Maple, and Pacific Dogwood, with floor vegetation including four species of fern, gooseberry, black cap raspberry, service berry, California grape, two Ceanothus species, poison oak, two manzanita species and mixed native grass and wildflower species. Note that lush ground vegetation on this property burned intensely during the 2017 Helena Fire, killing half the trees in this location (which have since been felled and removed).  Seedlings of fire-killed native tree and shrub species (e.g. pines, firs, cedar and manzanita) have re-established post-fire, while species such as Madrone, poison oak, Ceanothus, ferns and wildflowers are also regenerating from roots.
location_id: TMTL - with respect to diversity of mushroom species, plants, terrestrial and aquatic insects, anadromous salmonids, amphibians, reptiles, birds, and mammals.  Truly a naturalist's paradise.
source_type: Private, gated residential property.  Permission required in advance.  All trespassers prosecuted - individual or agency.

The soil is mainly red sand, where the top soil had been damaged due to runoff during the monsoon periods.

gen_desc: Auburn is located at 38°53′55″N 121°04′28″W.[16]

id: \nAccording to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 7.2 square miles (19 km2), of which 0.03 square miles (0.078 km2), or 0.38%, is water.

\nAuburn is situated in the Northern California foothills of the Sierra Nevada range, approximately 800 vertical feet above the confluence of the North Fork and Middle Fork of the American River. It is located between Sacramento and Reno, Nevada along Interstate 80. Mountainous wilderness canyons and the western slope of the Sierra Nevada lie adjacent eastward, while gentle rolling foothills well-suited for agriculture lie to the west. The crest of the Sierra Nevada lies approximately 45 miles (72 km) eastward, and the Central Valley lies approximately ten miles to the west.
location_id: Auburn has a hot-summer Mediterranean climate (Köppen Csa) that is characterized by cool, moist winters and hot, dry summers. Average December temperatures are a maximum of 54.4 °F (12.4 °C) and a minimum of 39 °F (4 °C). Average July temperatures are a maximum of 94.0 °F (34.4 °C) and a minimum of 61.0 °F (16.1 °C). Annually, there are an average of 59.4 days with highs of 90 °F (32 °C) or higher, an average of 7.0 days with 100 °F (38 °C) or higher, and an average of 17.1 days with 32 °F (0 °C) or lower.[17] The record high temperature was 113 °F (45 °C) on July 15, 1972. The record low temperature was 16 °F (−9 °C) on December 9, 1972 and December 7, 2009.[17]

id: \nAverage annual precipitation is 37.36 inches (949 mm). There are an average of 70 days with measurable precipitation. The wettest year was 1983 with 64.87 inches (1,648 mm) and the driest year was 1976 with 11.76 inches (299 mm). The most precipitation in one month was 23.08 inches (586 mm) in January 1909. The most precipitation in 24 hours was 5.41 inches (137 mm) on October 13, 1962,[17] during the Columbus Day Storm. Snow rarely falls in Auburn; average annual snowfall is only 0.0–1.0 inch (0–25 mm).[17] The most snowfall in one year was 10.7 inches (270 mm) in 1972, including 6.5 inches (170 mm) in January 1972.[18]

\nAuburn's Köppen classification and climate similarities to locations such as Napa, California and parts of Italy make it a suitable region for growing wine grapes. Auburn and the surrounding areas of Placer County are home to over 20 wineries.[19]

gen_desc: Cer (pronounced [tsɛr]) is a mountain in western Serbia, 30 kilometers from Šabac, 100 kilometers west of Belgrade. The highest peak has an elevation of 689 m (2,260 ft) above sea level. Cer is rich in the Turkey oak forests after which it was named.

Mountain Medvednik is located near the town of Valjevo (30km) and 1247 meters above sea level. It is situated in the center of the mountain range which starts near the Drina river and spreads to the west, ending in the vicinity of Belgrade.

id: \nMountain range which Medvednik is part off, starts with Gučevo in the west, and accross Boranja, Jagodnja and Sokolska planina continues to Valjevo mountains, consisting off Medvednik (1247 m above sea level), Jablanik (1274 m above sea level), Povlen (highest peak at 1347 m above sea level), Maljen (Kraljev sto, 1104 m above sea level), and ends with Suvobor and Rajac in the east.

\nMedvednik got its name from the fact that this mountain from the Valjevo side is seen as a big bear that is lying down to rest. Others claim that the mountain got its name from a large number of bears that were present here, but hunted heavily which caused local extinction.
location_id: In a series of Valjevo mountains, Medvednik is the most striking mountain from a distance, with its asymmetrical silhouette that rises slightly from the east to a plateau in the middle of the massif, to suddenly collapse with steep limestone cliffs at its western end. As the last mountain in the range, its peaks in the highest part exceed 1200 meters above sea level.

id: \nThe slopes are densely overgrown with beech forest , with good yields of mushrooms, and meadows with wild strawberries and medicinal herbs. Beech forest is thinning, while artificially introduced pine appears, and in the lower parts, cultural areas under raspberry and blackberry plantations are easily visible, which has a significant share in the income of the local population. The northern slopes are leaning from the east on the very close mountain Jablanik and the undulating plateaus of the upper basin of the river Jablanica.

gen_desc: Leeward slopes of the Koolau Mountains near the urban center of Honolulu, Hawaii.

location_id: Humidity and rainfall increase with elevation. Nuuanu Valley receives as much as 160" of rain a year. Subtropical Moist Forest is present at lower elevations, grading to Subtropical Montaine Rain Forest at higher elevations. Average humidity is 75% and average temperature is 75 F.

id: \nGeologically, Nuuanu Valley is a part of the flank of the Koolau Shield volcano. Bedrock is comprised exclusively of shield building basalt. The valley formed through extensive erosion of the volcano after activity ceased. Tropical soils and paleosols are present primarily as valley fill and along the tops of ridges.

\nAs with much of the Hawaiian Islands, introduction of invasive non-native species has dramatically altered the forest ecology of Nuuanu Valley. Little remains of the natural habitat. At elevation there are still some stands of primarily native vegetation. These locations are difficult to access and require advanced hiking ability.
\nNuuanu Valley is heavily developed at lower elevations, and is part of urban Honolulu. Only the uppermost elevations and steeper terrain is undisturbed.
source_type: Much of the undeveloped portion of Nuuanu Valley sits within the Honolulu Forest Watershed Reserve. And is publicly accessible. Numerous trails are available for hiking and are mapped.
